  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "Despite its name, this is **not a weather instrument**. An \"electric barometer\" is a demonstration device for the phenomenon of **barometric light** — the mysterious glow produced when mercury moves inside an evacuated glass tube. First observed by **Jean Picard** in 1675, this phenomenon is now understood as **triboelectric gas discharge / electroluminescence**: mercury sliding against glass generates static charge, which excites residual gas molecules in the vacuum, causing them to emit light. It is the same fundamental mechanism as a **neon lamp** — making this instrument a direct ancestor of electric lighting, created 90 years before Edison. Made in 1790, it belongs to the research programme of **Martinus van Marum**, who operated the world's largest electrostatic generator at Teylers and had just established the first physics laboratory in the Netherlands that same year.",
